#, no-wrap
msgid "Booting CDs"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <sections><section><subsection><title>
#: en/handbook/draft/complete/hb-app_arch-x86.xml:17
#, no-wrap
msgid "BIOS"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <sections><section><subsection><body><p>
#: en/handbook/draft/complete/hb-app_arch-x86.xml:21
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"The BIOS (Basic Input/Output System) is the first system started when you power\n"
"on your computer. It first performs a POST (Power-On Self Test) to verify if\n"
"your hardware is still in good shape. When the POST gives the BIOS an okay, the\n"
"BIOS will load the boot loader from the boot device configured in its memory.\n"
"This boot loader then fires up the operating system and the entire system dance\n"
"starts...\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <sections><section><subsection><body><p>
#: en/handbook/draft/complete/hb-app_arch-x86.xml:30
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"To boot from a CD, you need to configure your BIOS so that the CD-ROM device is\n"
"the first boot device. Reboot your system and fire up the BIOS. You will be\n"
"informed about what key to press right after (or during) the POST to get in the\n"
"BIOS setup. Most BIOSes use <c>Esc</c>, <c>F1</c>, <c>F2</c>, <c>DEL</c> or\n"
"<c>F8</c>.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <sections><section><subsection><body><p>
#: en/handbook/draft/complete/hb-app_arch-x86.xml:38
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Once you are inside the BIOS setup, search for the setting where you can change\n"
"the boot device sequence. Some BIOSes place it beneath <e>CMOS Setup</e>, but\n"
"there isn't a standard - each BIOS has its differences. Change the order so that\n"
"the CD-ROM device is mentioned first before the first hard disk (HD-0). Such a\n"
"setting will allow you to boot from a bootable CD if there is one in the CD-ROM\n"
"drive, or boot from the hard drive otherwise.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <sections><section><title>
#: en/handbook/draft/complete/hb-app_arch-x86.xml:51
#, no-wrap
msgid "Partitioning the disks"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <sections><section><subsection><title>
#: en/handbook/draft/complete/hb-app_arch-x86.xml:53
#, no-wrap
msgid "Partition layout"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <sections><section><subsection><body><p>
#: en/handbook/draft/complete/hb-app_arch-x86.xml:57
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Each disk on an x86 system can have at most <e>four</e> primary partitions.\n"
"This is a remnant of the old days when four partitions were considered enough.\n"
"Each primary partition has its identification inside the first sector on the\n"
"disk (the <e>boot record</e>). When you want more than four partitions, you\n"
"should configure one of the primary partitions to contain all the non-primary\n"
"partitions. This large primary partition is called the <e>extended</e> partition\n"
"and the partitions inside it are called <e>logical</e> partitions.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <sections><section><subsection><body><p>
#: en/handbook/draft/complete/hb-app_arch-x86.xml:67
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"The de facto standard device naming convention tells us that the primary\n"
"partitions for a disk are numbered as 1 to 4 while the logical ones are 5\n"
"and higher, regardless of how many primary partitions you use. The naming\n"
"convention also tells us how the disks themselves are named.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <sections><section><subsection><body><ul><li>
#: en/handbook/draft/complete/hb-app_arch-x86.xml:75
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"    IDE device names start with <path>hd</path> followed by an alphabetic\n"
"    character which resembles the location of the disk in the system: the\n"
"    primary master<sup>1</sup> is <path>hda</path>, the primary slave\n"
"    <path>hdb</path>, the secondary master <path>hdc</path>, etc.\n"
"  "
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <sections><section><subsection><body><ul><li>
#: en/handbook/draft/complete/hb-app_arch-x86.xml:81
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"    SCSI device names (and most Serial ATA ones as well) start with\n"
"    <path>sd</path> followed by an alphabetic character which resembles the\n"
"    position of the disk in the disk chain: the first one is <path>sda</path>,\n"
"    the second one <path>sdb</path>, etc.\n"
"  "
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <sections><section><subsection><body><p>
#: en/handbook/draft/complete/hb-app_arch-x86.xml:89
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Device files are located inside <path>/dev</path>, so if you want to identify\n"
"the primary master IDE drive you would state <path>/dev/hda</path>. \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <sections><section><subsection><body><note>
#: en/handbook/draft/complete/hb-app_arch-x86.xml:94
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"<sup>1</sup> IDE drives are controlled by an IDE controller. Each controller can\n"
"govern two IDE devices at most: a master and a slave. The master drive has\n"
"higher priority when both drives are attempting to send or receive data. A\n"
"standard x86 system has two controllers, a primary one (<path>ide0</path>) and a\n"
"secundary one (<path>ide1</path>). \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <sections><section><subsection><title>
#: en/handbook/draft/complete/hb-app_arch-x86.xml:104
#, no-wrap
msgid "Partitioning using cfdisk"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <sections><section><subsection><body><p>
#: en/handbook/draft/complete/hb-app_arch-x86.xml:108
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"The <c>cfdisk</c> tool allows you to quickly partition your disks and is a lot\n"
"easier to use than <c>fdisk</c>. When you have fired up <c>cfdisk</c> (which\n"
"selects <path>/dev/hda</path> by default - you can use a different disk by\n"
"giving the device file name as an argument) you will get an overview of the\n"
"available partitions, each one listed with the device name, partition type, file\n"
"system type and size.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <sections><section><subsection><body><p>
#: en/handbook/draft/complete/hb-app_arch-x86.xml:117
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"When you take a look at the interface, you'll notice that it is quite\n"
"self-explanatory:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <sections><section><subsection><body><ul><li>
#: en/handbook/draft/complete/hb-app_arch-x86.xml:123
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"    When you select a free space region, you can add new partitions by pressing\n"
"    <c>New</c>. <c>cfdisk</c> will ask you what kind of partition you want\n"
"    (primary or logical) and its size after which the partition is added to the\n"
"    overview pane.\n"
"  "
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <sections><section><subsection><body><ul><li>
#: en/handbook/draft/complete/hb-app_arch-x86.xml:129
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"    When you select a partition entry, you can change the file system type. Just\n"
"    select <c>Type</c> and search for the type you are interested in (probably\n"
"    82 - Linux swap / Solaris, or 83 - Linux).\n"
"  "
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <sections><section><subsection><body><ul><li>
#: en/handbook/draft/complete/hb-app_arch-x86.xml:134
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"    Since some BIOSes require the partition that stores the boot loader for the\n"
"    operating system to be marked as bootable, there is also an option of doing\n"
"    so.\n"
"  "
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <sections><section><subsection><body><p>
#: en/handbook/draft/complete/hb-app_arch-x86.xml:141
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"You should create your partitions, not forgetting to mark at least one of them\n"
"for swap usage. Even though swap files are supported by Linux, it is not\n"
"recommended since they have some impact on the system's performance. A dedicated\n"
"swap partition performs far better than a swap file.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <sections><section><subsection><body><p>
#: en/handbook/draft/complete/hb-app_arch-x86.xml:148
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"A frequently asked question is how to partition the disk. There is no satisfying\n"
"answer to that, and any attempt to obtain one will result in a cataclysmic\n"
"series of flamewars. So we'll stick with a simple suggestion: it doesn't hurt to\n"
"use two partitions: one for the entire Linux system and one for the swap space.\n"
"You'll get to know your own preferences when you are more experienced with\n"
"Linux.\n"
msgstr ""

